   <h1>Re: [T2] More Ball joint/torsion arm Questions</h1>
   <b>"Bill Harris" <biharris(-at-)cgmailbox.com></b><br/>
   <i>2002-05-17 06:13:33+00</i><br/>
   <br/>
   <pre>
----- Original Message -----
From: Brandt Hart 
To: 
Sent: Thursday, May 16, 2002 10:47 PM
Subject: [T2] More Ball joint/torsion arm Questions


> Hello list,
>
> I've been following the resent threads regarding ball joints. I just got
the
> bus-boys torsion arm set up the other day and hope to put them on my '78
> Westy tomorrow (friday). BTW No core charge and and they look great. I
too,
> have never done this procedure before and have some additional questions.
>
> 1)Do I have to do both sides at the same time?
No
> Is there some tension thing I am missing?
No, it will make sense when you get into it -- I presume you think before
you strike :-)
> Seems like I am (step 19 Mike Gensler, in Library)
>
> 2)My upper Bus-boys pre-pressed balljoints don't have the hex shaped
> "eccentric ring" on the upper ball joint. Should I be concerned?
No, its on the old one
>
> 3)Are the torsion arm seals NLA?
Yes
> Do they usually need to be replaced?
No
> And what about the needle bearing? (Bentley 2,18 Fig 7-16) Does a 78 have
this?
Yes
> and is it NLA?
Dunno
> or usually worn to the point of needing replacement?
No
>
> 4)Should I use anti seize on anything when I put it back together?
Up to you, I didn't
> Is it worth getting a socket that fits the ball joint nuts for proper
torque?
I used a SAE I think it was 1 1/16
> And What kind of grease should I buy? Brand, type?
For non high-speed apps, I use a good Moly compound
>
> Also, I ordered (Bus Depot) tie rods, all four shocks, all new brake
> pads/shoes and rear clyinders, front brake hoses, plus other stuff. Every
> rubber seal/boot in the front end of this bus is shot. Now I find myself
> wondering if I should do the front wheel bearings and swing lever bushings
> while I'm at it.
>
> 5)Would this make sense? (bearings, swing lever bushings)
I'd do the bearings for sure, there's a lot riding on those little steel
cylinders -- I use Redline CV-2 Synthetic for all high-speed apps (CV, wheel
bearing)
>
> I have no clue as to how many miles the bus has on it as the speedo was
> broken when I bought the bus in Feb (milage "exempt" on title). The bus
was
> not well cared for either but, has no rust and will someday take the place
> of my rusty '79 westy. I want something that will last a long time,
> reliable....
>
> 6)Finally, any tips for the stabilizer bar clamps? the one with the slide
on
> clip. C-clamp maybe?
PITA - 3 popped right off (I did 2 busses a few weeks ago) one required the
air hammer, 4lb sledge, increasingly bigger drifts.  Wanted to reuse the
bushing so we didn't go to the torch-wrench.
>
> Thanks in advance and sorry this turned out to be so long. I'm sure things
> will become much clearer when I start ripping things apart in the morning.
>
> Thanks a million,
> Brandt
> '78 Sagegreen Westfalia
> '79 Sagegreen Westfalia
>
> _________________________________________________________________
> Join the world's largest e-mail service with MSN Hotmail.
> http://www.hotmail.com
>
></pre>


